{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c83770d6-d79f-4c99-9d2b-23c017096df4","content":"Two things change with xUnit v3 + MTP:\n\n1. **`--filter` → `--treenode-filter`** — MTP uses a tree-path syntax instead of VSTest's property syntax.\n2. **Syntax** — node matching uses glob-style paths; traits go in `[key=value]` brackets.\n\n**Your old VSTest filter:**\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n**Equivalent MTP tree-node filter:**\n```\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*/**[Category=Smoke]\"\n```\n\n### How it maps\n\n| VSTest concept | MTP tree-node filter |\n|---|---|\n| `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` (contains) | `/**/*IntegrationTests*/**` (glob wildcard match on the test tree path) |\n| `&` (AND) | Just append the property filter to the same node |\n| `Category=Smoke` (trait) | `[Category=Smoke]` (bracket property syntax) |\n\nThe `--` separator tells `dotnet test` to pass arguments through to the MTP runner. No code changes are needed — your `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]` attributes work the same in xUnit v3.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88d6bb9e-bf45-4962-8929-97cc3611283b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is migrating from xUnit v2 to xUnit v3 with Microsoft Testing Platform (MTP). The key changes for filtering:\n\n1. With xUnit v2 + VSTest adapter, `dotnet test --filter` used VSTest filter syntax: `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke`\n2. With xUnit v3 + MTP (`UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner=true`), the filter syntax changes. MTP uses `--filter` but with different syntax.\n\nKey differences:\n- MTP uses `--treenode-filter` (or `--filter` depending on version) with a different syntax\n\n\n- The tree-node filter syntax follows a path structure like `/FullAssemblyPath/Namespace/Class/Method` for matching tests by name, and traits are specified with bracket notation like `[Category=Smoke]`\n- So the VSTest filter `FullyQualifiedNa